%T A397396 -2,0,2,3,2,1,3,4,3,2,0,-2,-3,-4,-2,-1,-3,-5,-4,-3,-2,0,2,3,4,5,4,2,4,
%U A397396 5,4,3,1,-1,-3,-4,-5,-3,-1,-3,-1,-3,-2,-4,-3,-1
%N A397396 a(n) is the x-coordinate of a knight after moving n steps according to the rules defined in A397392, with the last tiebreaking rule modified so that the lexicographically least point is chosen instead of the lexicographically largest point.
%C A397396 The last tiebreaking rule, which chooses the lexicographically least point, seems never to come into play, except for the very first step.
%C A397396 Backtracking (discarding a candidate move because it inevitably leads to a dead end) is needed for the first time in the 756th step, in which the step to (-1,-15) is discarded because all its neighbors are already visited. Instead the knight moves to (-1,-19). (-1,-15) is also the position closest to the origin of the positions that are never visited. Among the first 1000000 steps, backtracking is needed 114 times. The majority of the discarded steps are steps to boundary points (points with |x|==1 and y<0).
%C A397396 The first time the 3rd differences need to be compared is at the 8811th step. Among the first 1000000 steps, differences of order higher than 3 never need to be compared; 3rd differences are needed 8 times.
